Interpretation of patients QS habits as psychosomatic markers of distress, obsessiveness, hypochondria, disorders.
Data are only useful when clinicians can trust the data, sampling and collection methods, & measurement instruments.
Data only useful if they fulfill information needs identified by decision-making cognitive flow.
Data only appear relevant and useful when organised, contextualised and represented in a way conforms to prior training.
Data useful when they support top-down clinical decision-making processes, which are often organised around risk mitigation.

Core to the vision of eHealth is empowering patients to make more accurate and detailed records of their daily wellbeing so that this information can be used to better diagnose and identify treatments most appropriate for their condition and lifestyle. Personal tracking devices and apps have become extremely popular, and the collection of information in this way is called The Quantified Self.

However, a persistent challenge is where this information intersects clinical practice. Any introduction of inaccurate information may introduce an increased risk of misdiagnosis. Second, medical professionals, being human, are influenced by cognitive biases that can mean that even irrelevant information may contribute to errors.
How might patient-supplied information be made to safe for use in clinical decision making settings? Are there social, technological or combined solutions? We explore these questions here.
A Case of The Dizzy Student
We presented doctors in the UK and US with two scenarios involving patient-generated data. We asked them to think aloud as they described the next steps they would take toward a diagnosis.
I had a previous patient who presented in the same way
Pulse not useful. Blood pressure would have been more useful
This data justifies a number of tests, which will give me time to think.
The patient is obsessive, there's possibly something psychological
The scenarios only slowly contextualised the situation - e.g. "middle aged" only introduced later
